''\n| {{nowrap|March 22, 2018}}\n| {{nowrap|June 28, 2018}}\n|'''{{nowrap|[[Aquaria (drag queen)|Aquaria]]}}'''\n|{{nowrap|[[Eureka O'Hara]]}}<br />{{nowrap|[[Kameron Michaels]]}}\n|{{nowrap|[[Mon\u00e9t X Change]]}}\n|\n* $100,000\n* A one-year supply of Anastasia Beverly Hills cosmetics\n* A crown and scepter from Fierce Drag Jewels\n|-\n! '''[[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 11)|11]]'''\n| {{nowrap|February 28, 2019}}\n| {{nowrap|May 30, 2019}}\n|'''[[Yvie Oddly]]'''\n|{{nowrap|[[Brooke Lynn Hytes]]}}\n|{{nowrap|[[Nina West]]}}\n|\n* $100,000\n* A one-year supply of Anastasia Beverly Hills cosmetics\n* A crown and scepter from Fierce Drag Jewels\n|-\n! '''[[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 12)|12]]'''\n| {{nowrap|February 28, 2020}}\n| {{nowrap|TBA}}\n| '''{{nowrap|TBA}}'''\n| {{nowrap|TBA}}\n| {{nowrap|TBA}}\n|\n* $100,000\n* A one-year supply of Anastasia Beverly Hills cosmetics\n* A crown and scepter from Fierce Drag Jewels\n|-\n|}\n\n===Season 1 (2009)===\n{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race (season 1)}}\n[[File:BeBe Zahara Benet.jpg|thumb|right|Season 1 winner [[BeBe Zahara Benet]]|207x207px]]\n\nThe first season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' premiered in the United States on February 2, 2009, on [[Logo TV|Logo]].\n\nNine contestants were selected to compete in the running of becoming \"America's Next Drag Superstar.\" The winner of the first season won a lifetime supply of [[MAC Cosmetics]], was featured on the cover of [[Paper Magazine]], was featured in an LA Eyeworks campaign, joined the Absolut Pride tour, and won a cash prize of $20,000. One of the nine contestants to compete on ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' was determined by an audience vote via the show's official website. The results were announced in early September 2008. The contestant to win this honor was [[Nina Flowers]] from [[Bayam\u00f3n, Puerto Rico]] (currently residing in [[Denver, Colorado]]).  The theme song playing during the runway every episode was \"[[Cover Girl (RuPaul song)|Cover Girl]]\" from RuPaul's album ''[[Champion (RuPaul album)|Champion]]''.\n\nThe winner of the first season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' was [[BeBe Zahara Benet]], with [[Nina Flowers]] winning Miss Congeniality.\n\nIn late 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://press.logotv.com/press-releases/2014/05/27/gentlemen-re-start-your-engines-and-may-the-best-woman-win-again|title=Gentlemen, Re-Start Your Engines...and May the Best Woman Win...Again!|last=Shumaker|first=Jason|date=August 18, 2013|publisher=[[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]]|accessdate=August 17, 2015|author2=Jake Slane|work=Logo Press Room}}</ref> Logo re-aired the first season, which was titled ''RuPaul's Drag Race: The Lost Season Ru-Vealed'', and featured commentary from RuPaul.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10151663349732828&set=a.156472877827.118955.31772462827&type=1&comment_id=9992661&reply_comment_id=9992723&total_comments=15 | title= Callie, dear...|publisher=RuPaul's Drag Race Facebook page|date=September 23, 2013 |accessdate=August 17, 2015|quote=Callie, dear...}}</ref>\n<!-- To edit the episodes in this section, you need to edit the article listed above. -->\n\n===Season 2 (2010)===\n{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race (season 2)}}\n[[File:Tyra-sanchez-8c26d75c-81bc-4696-83a3-0a25bf57179-resize-750.jpg|thumb|181x181px|Season 2 winner [[Tyra Sanchez]]]]\nFor season two, the number of contestants was increased from nine to twelve, and the prizes were slightly modified: a lifetime supply of Nyx Cosmetics and be the face of nyxcosmetics.com, an exclusive one year public relations contract with [[LGBT]] firm Project Publicity, be featured an LA Eyeworks campaign, join the [[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]] Drag Race tour, and a cash prize of $25,000. A new tradition of writing a farewell message in lipstick on the workstation mirror was started by the first eliminated queen of the season, [[Shangela Laquifa Wadley]]. The theme song playing during the runway and the end credits each episode is \"[[Jealous of My Boogie]]\" from RuPaul's album ''[[Champion (RuPaul album)|Champion]]''. Each week's episode is followed by a behind-the-scenes show, ''RuPaul's Drag Race Untucked''.\n\nThe winner of the second season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' was [[Tyra Sanchez]], with [[Pandora Boxx]] winning Miss Congeniality.\n\nOn December 6, 2011, [[Amazon.com]] released this season on DVD via their CreateSpace program.<ref name=Amazon.com>{{cite web|last=Kline|first=Dill|title=Rupauls' Drag Race Season 2 Pre-Orders|url=https://www.amazon.com/RuPauls-Drag-Race-Season-2/dp/B005UQQR06/ref=sr_1_6?ie=UTF8&qid=1319228919&sr=8-6|accessdate=August 17, 2015}}</ref>\n<!-- To edit the episodes in this section, you need to edit the article listed above. -->\n\n===Season 3 (2011)===\n{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race (season 3)}}\n[[File:Raja Gemini (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|right|Season 3 winner [[Sutan Amrull|Raja]]]]\n\nThis season had [[Michelle Visage]] replacing Merle Ginsberg on the judging panel and Billy Brasfield<ref>{{cite web|last=Brasfield|first=Billy|url=http://www.billybbeauty.com/site/bio_all.html|title=Billy Brasfield Official Biography}}</ref> (commonly known as Billy B), [[Mike Ruiz]], and Jeffrey Moran (courtesy of [[Absolut Vodka]]) filling in for [[Santino Rice]]'s absence during several episodes. Due to Billy B's continued appearances, he and Rice are considered to have been alternate judges for the same seat on judges panel.<ref name=\"billyb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logotv.com/video/episode-16-season-3-reunited/1662947/playlist.jhtml#vid=647523|title=Ep. 16, Episode 16, Season 3: Reunited!|publisher=[[Logo TV]]|accessdate=August 17, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107020503/http://www.logotv.com/video/episode-16-season-3-reunited/1662947/playlist.jhtml#vid=647523|archivedate=November 7, 2014|df=}}</ref> Other changes made included the introduction of a wildcard contestant from the past season, Shangela; an episode with no elimination; and a contestant, [[Carmen Carrera]], being brought back into the competition after having been eliminated a few episodes prior. A new pit crew was also introduced consisting of Jason Carter and Shawn Morales. The theme song playing during the runway each episode was changed to \"Champion\" while the song playing during the credits is \"Main Event\", both from RuPaul's album ''[[Champion (RuPaul album)|Champion]]''. As with [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 2)|the previous season]], each week's episode was followed by a behind-the-scenes show, ''RuPaul's Drag Race: Untucked''.\n\nThe winner of the third season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' was [[Raja Gemini|Raja]], with [[Yara Sofia]] winning Miss Congeniality.\n\nOn December 6, 2011 Amazon.com released this season on DVD via their CreateSpace program.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kline|first=Dill|url=https://www.amazon.com/RuPauls-Drag-Race-Season-3/dp/B005UQQRBA/ref=sr_1_6?s=movies-tv&ie=UTF8&qid=1319310966&sr=1-6|title=RuPauls Drag Race Season 3|accessdate=August 17, 2015}}</ref>\n<!-- To edit the episodes in this section, you need to edit the article listed above. -->\n\n===Season 4 (2012)===\n{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race (season 4)}}\n[[File:Rupaul Dragcon 2018-281 (41377497904).jpg|thumb|Season 4 winner [[Sharon Needles]]|194x194px]]\n\nThe fourth season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' began airing on January 30, 2012,<ref name=\"announce\">{{cite web |url=http://www.newnownext.com/rupauls-drag-race-season-4-judges-glee-modern-family-amber-riley-jesse-tyler-ferguson/10/2011/ | title = RuPaul's Drag Race Season 4 Judges: Think Glee, Modern Family! | accessdate = October 12, 2011 | last = Polly | first = John | date = October 10, 2011 | work = NewNowNext | publisher = [[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]]}}</ref> with cast members announced November 13, 2011.<ref name=\"cast\">{{cite web |url=http://www.logotv.com/shows/rupauls_drag_race/season_4/series.jhtml | title = Rupaul's Drag Race Season 4 | accessdate = November 15, 2011 | publisher = [[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]]}}</ref>\n\nThe winner of season four headlined [[Logo (TV channel)|Logo's]] Drag Race Tour featuring [[Absolut Vodka]], won a one-of-a-kind trip, a lifetime supply of NYX Cosmetics, a cash prize of [[United States dollar|$]]100,000, and the title of \"America's Next Drag Superstar.\"<ref name=\"press1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.logopressroom.com/press-release/halleloo-%E2%80%9Crupaul%E2%80%99s-drag-race%E2%80%9D-returns-to-logo-for-a-new-season-of-outrageous-reality-competition-in-january-2012/|title=HALLELOO! \"RUPAUL'S DRAG RACE\" RETURNS TO LOGO FOR A NEW SEASON OF OUTRAGEOUS REALITY COMPETITION IN JANUARY 2012|accessdate=August 17, 2015|last=Shumaker|first=Jason|author2=Jake Slane |date=November 14, 2011|work=Logo Press Room|publisher=[[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]]}}</ref> Like the previous season, Santino Rice and Billy B (Billy Brasfield), shared the same seat at the judges table alternatively, with Brasfield filling in for Rice when needed.<ref name=\"billyb\"/> Both judges appeared side by side in the audience during the \"Reunited\" episode.\n\nThe winner of the fourth season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' was [[Sharon Needles]], with [[Latrice Royale]] winning Miss Congeniality.\n\nThe theme song playing during the runway every episode was \"Glamazon\" and the song played during the credits was \"The Beginning\", both from RuPaul's album ''[[Glamazon (album)|Glamazon]]''.\n<!-- To edit the episodes in this section, you need to edit the article listed above. -->\n\n===Season 5 (2013)===\n{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race (season 5)}}\n[[File:Jinkx Monsoon 08.jpg|thumb|right|Season 5 winner [[Jinkx Monsoon]]|207x207px]]\n\nThe fifth season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' began airing on January 28, 2013, with a 90-minute premiere episode. It had the most contestants since the inaugural season of the show with a total number of fourteen.\n\nSeason five's winner walked away with the title of \"America's Next Drag Superstar\" along with a lifetime supply of Colorevolution Cosmetics, a one-of-a-kind trip courtesy of AlandChuck.travel, a headlining spot on [[Logo (TV channel)|Logo's]] Drag Race Tour featuring [[Absolut Vodka]] and a cash prize of $100,000. Santino Rice and Michelle Visage were back as judges on the panel.<ref name='Press1'>{{cite web|url=http://www.logopressroom.com/press-release/rpdr5premiere/|title =\"THE QUEENS OF \"RUPAUL'S DRAG RACE\" SEASON FIVE BEGIN THEIR BATTLE FOR THE CROWN ON MONDAY, JANUARY 28 ON LOGO|accessdate=August 17, 2015|last=Shumaker|first=Jason|author2=Jake Slane|date= December 10, 2012|work=Logo Press Room|publisher=[[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]]}}</ref> The theme song played during the runway each episode is \"I Bring the Beat\", while the song playing during the credits is \"The Beginning\", both songs are from RuPaul's album ''[[Glamazon (album)|Glamazon]]''.\n\nThe winner of the fifth season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' was [[Jinkx Monsoon]], with [[Ivy Winters]] winning Miss Congeniality.\n<!-- To edit the episodes in this section, you need to edit the article listed above. -->\n\n===Season 6 (2014)===\n{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race (season 6)}}\n[[File:Bianca Del Rio, Rolodex of Hate Tour, Theater Amsterdam 2015.jpg|thumb|right|Season 6 winner [[Bianca Del Rio]]|209x209px]]\n\nThe sixth season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' began airing February 24, 2014.\n\nLike [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 5)|the fifth season]], this season featured fourteen contestants competing for the title of \"America's Next Drag Superstar\". For the first time in the show's history, the season premiere was split into two episodes; the fourteen queens are split into two groups and the seven queens in each group compete against one another before being united as one group in the third episode.\n\nSantino Rice and Michelle Visage are back as judges at the panel. Two new pit crew members, Miles Moody and Simon Sherry-Wood, joined Jason Carter and Shawn Morales.<ref>{{cite web | url =\nhttp://www.out.com/entertainment/popnography/2014/02/19/meet-rupauls-drag-races-new-bulgier-pit-crew| title = Meet RuPaul's Drag Race's New, Bulgier Pit Crew | accessdate = February 22, 2014 | last = Lambe | first = Stacy | date = February 19, 2014 | work = out.com, Popnography}}</ref> The winner of this season won a prize package that included a supply from Colorevolution Cosmetics and a cash prize of $100,000.<ref name='Press2'>{{cite web | url =\nhttp://www.logopressroom.com/uncategorized/let-the-transformations-beginrupauls-drag-race-returns-to-logo-tv-for-a-sixth-season-on-monday-february-24th-at-9-pm-etpt/| title = \"LET THE TRANSFORMATIONS BEGIN!...\"RUPAULS DRAG RACE\" RETURNS TO LOGO TV FOR A SIXTH SEASON ON MONDAY, FEBRUARY 24TH AT 9 PM ET/PT | accessdate = January 13, 2014 | last = Shumaker | first = Jason |author2=Jake Slane  | date = January 13, 2014 | work = Logo Press Room | publisher = [[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]]}}</ref> This was the first season where [[Absolut Vodka]] and Interior Illusions, Inc. were not sponsors for the show, more specifically for the ''Untucked'' episodes. The Interior Illusions Lounge is now  known as the Silver Lounge or FormDecor Lounge. The theme song played during the runway segment each episode was \"Sissy That Walk\" while the song playing during the credits is \"Dance With U\", both from the album ''[[Born Naked]]''.\n\nThe winner of the sixth season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' was [[Bianca Del Rio]], with [[BenDeLaCreme]] winning Miss Congeniality.\n<!-- To edit the episodes in this section, you need to edit the article listed above. -->\n\n===Season 7 (2015)===\n{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race (season 7)}}\n[[File:Violet Chachki at DragCon, April 2017.png|thumb|right|Season 7 winner [[Violet Chachki]]|196x196px]]\n\nThe seventh season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' began airing on March 2, 2015.\n\nReturning judges included [[RuPaul]] and [[Michelle Visage]], while the space previously occupied by [[Santino Rice]] was filled by new additions [[Ross Mathews]] and [[Carson Kressley]].<ref name=HuffPost>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/01/28/drag-race-season-seven-premiere_n_6555636.html|title='RuPaul's Drag Race' Adds New Judges, Will Premiere March 2|accessdate=August 17, 2015|date=January 28, 2015|work=Huffington Post}}</ref> Mathews and Kressley were both present for the season premiere and then took turns sharing judging responsibilities. Shawn Morales, a member of the Pit Crew since [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 3)|the third season]] and Simon Sherry-Wood, a member in [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 6)|the sixth season]], did not appear this season and were replaced by Bryce Eilenberg.\n\nLike the previous two seasons of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'', the season featured fourteen contestants competing for the title of \"America's Next Drag Superstar\", a one-year supply of Anastasia Beverly Hills cosmetics, and a cash prize of $100,000. The season premiere debuted with a live and same-day viewership of 348,000, a 20% increase from the previous season. On March 20, 2015, it was announced that LogoTV had given the series an early renewal for an eighth season.<ref name=\"s7\">{{cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/rupauls-drag-race-season-8-renewal-1201456543/ |title='RuPaul's Drag Race' Renewed for Season 8 at Logo |accessdate=August 17, 2015 |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\nThe winner of the seventh season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' was [[Violet Chachki]], with [[Katya Zamolodchikova|Katya]] winning Miss Congeniality.\n<!-- To edit the episodes in this section, you need to edit the article listed above. -->\n\n===Season 8 (2016)===\n{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race (season 8)}}\n[[File:Bob The Drag Queen at Rupaul's Dragcon 2017 by dvsross.jpg|thumb|right|Season 8 winner [[Bob the Drag Queen]]|188x188px]]\n\nThe eighth season of RuPaul's Drag Race began airing on March 7, 2016, with cast members announced during the 2016 [[NewNowNext Awards|New Now Next Honors]] on February 1, 2016.\n\nMichelle Visage returned as a main judge, while Carson Kressley and Ross Mathews returned as rotating main judges.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Avery|first1=Dan|title=The Cast Of ''RuPaul{{'}}s Drag Race'' Season 8 Will Be Announced At New Now Next Honors|url=http://www.newnownext.com/the-cast-of-rupauls-drag-race-season-8-will-be-announced-at-new-now-next-honors/01/2016/|website=New Now Next|publisher=[[Viacom International Inc.]]|accessdate=January 14, 2016|location=United States|date=January 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe first episode celebrated the 100th taping of the show, and the 100th drag queen to enter the work room. Similar to the [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 2)|second season]] of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'', the season featured twelve contestants competing for the title of \"America's Next Drag Superstar\", a one-year supply of Anastasia Beverly Hills cosmetics, and a cash prize of $100,000.\n\nThe winner of the eighth season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' was [[Bob the Drag Queen]], with [[Cynthia Lee Fontaine]] winning Miss Congeniality.\n<!-- To edit the episodes in this section, you need to edit the article listed above. -->\n\n===Season 9 (2017)===\n{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race (season 9)}}\n[[File:Sasha Velour (cropped) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Season 9 winner [[Sasha Velour]]|178x178px]]\n\nThe ninth season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' began airing on March 24, 2017, with cast members being announced on February 2, 2017.\n\nMichelle Visage returned as a main judge, while Carson Kressley and Ross Mathews returned as rotating main judges.\n\nThis season features fourteen contestants competing for the title of \"America's Next Drag Superstar\", a one-year supply of Anastasia Beverly Hills cosmetics, and a cash prize of $100,000. The ninth season aired on VH1, with encore presentations continuing to air on Logo.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|title=''RuPaul's Drag Race'' Moves From Logo To VH1, More Viacom Show Shifts To Come?|url=http://deadline.com/2017/03/rupauls-drag-race-moves-logo-vh1-viacom-series-shift-1202032976/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|accessdate=March 1, 2017|location=United States|date=March 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Gennis|first1=Sadie|title=''RuPaul's Drag Race'' Gets Season 9 Premiere Date \u2013 and a New Network!|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/rupauls-drag-race-gets-season-9-premiere-vh1/|website=[[TVGuide]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=March 1, 2017|location=United States|language=en|date=March 1, 2017}}</ref> This season featured the return of [[Cynthia Lee Fontaine]], who previously participated in the series' eighth season. The ninth season featured a top four in the finale episode, as opposed to the top three, which was previously established in the fourth season. This season featured a twist in the finale called \"Lipsync for the Crown\" where there will be two rounds of lipsyncs and the winner of both lipsyncs will move ahead to the final lipsync and who ever wins the final lipsync will be declared as the winner.\n\nThe winner of the ninth season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' was [[Sasha Velour]], with [[Valentina (drag queen)|Valentina]] winning Miss Congeniality.\n\n===Season 10 (2018) ===\n{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race (season 10)}}\n[[File:Aquaria at Dragcon by dvsross.jpg|thumb|right|Season 10 winner [[Aquaria (drag queen)|Aquaria]]|191x191px]]\n\nThe tenth season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' began airing on March 22, 2018.\n\nMichelle Visage returned as a main judge, while Carson Kressley and Ross Mathews returned as rotating main judges.\n\nThis season features thirteen new contestants, and one returning contestant, competing for the title of \"America's Next Drag Superstar\", a one-year supply of Anastasia Beverly Hills cosmetics, and a cash prize of $100,000. [[Eureka O'Hara]], who was removed from the ninth season due to an injury, returned to the show after she accepted an open invitation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2017/04/21/rupauls-drag-race-eureka-returning-season-10-exit-interview/|title=Drag Race's Surprise Eliminee: 'I'm Definitely Going Back' for Season 10|last=Swift|first=Andy|last2=Swift|first2=Andy|date=2017-04-22|website=TVLine|access-date=2017-05-11}}</ref> The tenth season of ''Drag Race'' premiered; alongside the televised return of ''Untucked''.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Nolfi|first=Joey|title=RuPaul's Drag Race&nbsp;season 10 and&nbsp;Untucked&nbsp;will sashay to VH1 in March|url=http://ew.com/tv/2018/02/16/rupauls-drag-race-season-10-premiere-date/|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=February 16, 2018}}</ref> The tenth season featured a top four in the finale episode, as opposed to the top three, which was previously established in the fourth season.\n\nThe winner of the tenth season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' was [[Aquaria (drag queen)|Aquaria]], with [[Mon\u00e9t X Change]] winning Miss Congeniality.\n\n===Season 11 (2019) ===\n{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race (season 11)}}\n[[File:Dragcon-25 (47937194866).jpg|thumb|right|upright|Season 11 winner [[Yvie Oddly]]]]\n\nThe eleventh season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' began airing February 28, 2019. This season has a record-breaking fifteen contestants total, whereas previous seasons typically stuck to fourteen contestants consistently.\n\nMichelle Visage returned as a main judge, while Carson Kressley and Ross Mathews returned as rotating main judges.\n\nThis season features fourteen new contestants, and one returning contestant, competing for the title of \"America's Next Drag Superstar\", a one-year supply of Anastasia Beverly Hills cosmetics, and a cash prize of $100,000. This season saw return of [[Vanessa Vanjie Mateo]], who was first eliminated in the tenth season. The eleventh season featured a top four in the finale episode, as opposed to the top three, which was previously established in the fourth season. As with [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 10)|the previous season]], each week's episode was followed by an episode of the televised return of ''RuPaul's Drag Race: Untucked''.\n\nThe winner of the eleventh season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' was [[Yvie Oddly]], with [[Nina West]] winning Miss Congeniality.\n\n===Season 12 (2020) ===\n{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race (season 12)}}\nOn January 22, 2019, casting for the twelfth season was announced via YouTube and Twitter and was closed on March 1, 2019. On August 19, 2019, it was announced that the series had been renewed for a twelfth season.<ref>{{cite web |last=Swift |first=Andy |title=''RuPaul's Drag Race'' Renewed for Season 12; ''All Stars 5'' Also Ordered |url=https://tvline.com/2019/08/19/rupauls-drag-race-season-12-renewed-all-stars-5-watch-video/ |website=[[TVLine]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=August 19, 2019 |archiveurl=https://www.freezepage.com/1566232511XKZAGGGMPV |archivedate=August 19, 2019 |location=United States |language=en |date=August 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\nThe season began airing on February 28, 2020. The twelfth season includes celebrity judges such as [[Nicki Minaj]], [[Normani]], [[Whoopi Goldberg]], [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]], [[Chaka Khan|Chaka Khan,]] [[Robyn]], [[Leslie Jones (comedian)|Leslie Jones]], [[Jeff Goldblum]], [[Daisy Ridley]], [[Thandie Newton]], [[Olivia Munn]], [[Rachel Bloom]], [[Daniel Franzese]], [[Jonathan Bennett (actor)|Jonathan Bennett]] and [[Winnie Harlow]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/entertainment/tv/a28207309/rupauls-drag-race-season-12/|title=Hi, Just Answering All Your \u2018RuPaul\u2019s Drag Race\u2019 Season 12 Questions|last=Bonner|first=Mehera|last2=Chambers|first2=Hannah|date=2020-02-13|website=Cosmopolitan|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n\n===Season 13===\nOn December 2, 2019, casting for the thirteenth season was announced via YouTube and Twitter. The casting call closed on January 24, 2020.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n==Contestants==\n{{Main|List of RuPaul's Drag Race contestants}}\n\n==Specials==\n===''RuPaul's Drag Race: Green Screen Christmas'' (2015)===\nOn December 13, 2015, Logo aired a seasonal themed episode of ''RuPaul's Drag Race''. The non-competitive special episode was released in conjunction with RuPaul's holiday album ''[[Slay Belles]]'' and featured music videos for songs from the album. The cast included RuPaul, Michelle Visage, [[Siedah Garrett]], and [[Todrick Hall]], and former contestants [[Alyssa Edwards]], [[Laganja Estranja]], [[Latrice Royale]], [[Sutan Amrull|Raja]], and [[Shangela]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ru-Cap \"RuPaul's Green Screen Christmas\" Extravaganza With A TON of GIFs!|url=https://worldofwonder.net/ru-live-rupauls-green-screen-christmas-with-a-ton-of-gifs/ |website=[[World of Wonder (company)|WOW]]|accessdate=November 1, 2018|date=December 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= 'RuPaul's Drag Race: Green Screen Christmas' Holiday Special to Air Dec. 13|url= https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/heres-how-you-can-ring-in-the-holidays-with-rupaul_us_565f1394e4b072e9d1c437f2?guccounter=1 |website=[[Huffington Post]] |accessdate= November 1, 2018|date=December 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= This Sneak Peek of RuPaul's Drag Race Christmas Special Will Jingle Your Bells |url= https://www.tvguide.com/news/rupauls-drag-race-christmas-special-happy-holigays/ |website=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=November 1, 2018 |date= December 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===''RuPaul's Drag Race Holi-slay Spectacular'' (2018)===\n{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race Holi-slay Spectacular}}\nOn November 1, 2018, VH1 announced a seasonal themed special episode of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' scheduled to air on December 7, 2018. The special saw eight former contestants compete for the title of America's first Drag Race Christmas Queen.<ref>{{cite web |last=Nolfi |first=Joel |title=RuPaul's Drag Race to reunite eight queens for holiday competition episode|url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/11/01/rupaul-drag-race-holiday-special-premiere-date/ |website=[[EW.com]]|accessdate=November 1, 2018|date=November 1, 2018}}</ref> In the same announcement, the eight contestants confirmed to be competing were [[Eureka O'Hara]], [[Jasmine Masters]], [[Kim Chi (drag queen)|Kim Chi]], [[Latrice Royale]], [[Mayhem Miller (drag queen)|Mayhem Miller]], [[Shangela]], [[Sonique (drag queen)|Sonique]], and [[Trixie Mattel]].<ref>{{cite web |last=McHenry |first=Jackson |title=It's the Most Ru-nderful Time of the Year! Drag Race Is Making a Holi-Slay Spectacular|url=http://www.vulture.com/2018/11/rupauls-drag-race-holiday-spectacular.html |website=[[Vulture.com|Vulture]]|accessdate=November 1, 2018|date=November 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Colburn |first=Randall |title=RuPaul to crown America's first Drag Race Xmas Queen on new holiday special|url=https://news.avclub.com/rupaul-to-crown-americas-first-drag-race-xmas-queen-on-1830156705 |website=AV Club |accessdate=November 1, 2018|date=November 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===''RuPaul\u2019s Celebrity Drag Race'' (2020)===\n{{Main|RuPaul's Celebrity Drag Race}}\nOn April 10, 2020, VH1 announced a celebrity edition of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' titled \u2018RuPaul\u2019s Secret Celebrity Drag Race\u2019 was scheduled to air for four weeks beginning on April 24, 2020. The four-part event series will feature a trio of celebrities opening up their hearts and minds to the transformative power of drag. After getting some help from beloved past contestants \u2014 deemed \u201cQueen Supremes\u201d \u2014 [[Alyssa Edwards]], [[Asia O'Hara]], [[Bob the Drag Queen]], [[Kim Chi]], [[Mon\u00e9t X Change]], [[Monique Heart]], [[Nina West]], [[Trinity the Tuck]], [[Trixie Mattel]] and [[Vanessa Vanjie Mateo]], the celebrity contestants will compete in fan-favorite challenges and step onto the runway in their new looks with one of that week\u2019s three celebrity contestants will win the title of \u201cAmerica\u2019s Next Celebrity Drag Race Superstar\u201d and prize money for a charity of their choice.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Turchiano |first1=Danielle |title=VH1 Announces \u2018RuPaul\u2019s Secret Celebrity Drag Race\u2019 |url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/rupauls-secret-celebrity-drag-race-vh1-april-premiere-1234576364/ |website=Variety |accessdate=10 April 2020 |language=en |date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n{{main|RuPaul discography}}\nMost of the music used in the series comes from RuPaul's albums,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tunefind.com/show/rupauls-drag-race|title=Music from RuPaul's Drag Race|website=Tunefind|language=en-us|access-date=2018-12-07}}</ref> with the exception of songs used during the lip sync portion of the show and original music challenges.\n\n===Music videos===\nDuring seasons 1\u20138, the top queens must lip sync to and sometimes record a verse for a new RuPaul music video. From season 9 and All Stars 2 onward, the finale music video was replaced by the queens recording new verses to a RuPaul song and perform it with full choreography on the main stage.\n* \"CoverGirl\" (feat. [[BeBe Zahara Benet]], [[Nina Flowers]], & [[Rebecca Glasscock]]) (season 1)\n* \"[[Jealous of My Boogie|Jealous of My Boogie\" (Gomi & RasJek Mix)]] from ''Jealous of My Boogie - The RuMixes'' and ''Essential, Vol. 2'' (season 2)\n* \"Champion\" (DJ BunJoe's Olympic Mix) from ''Drag Race'' (season 3)\n* \"Glamazon\" from ''[[Glamazon (album)|Glamazon]]'' (season 4)\n* \"The Beginning\" from ''Glamazon'' (season 5)\n* \"Sissy That Walk\" from ''[[Born Naked]]'' (season 6)\n* \"Born Naked\" (Stadium Remix) (feat. Clairy Browne) from ''Realness'' (season 7)\n* \"The Realness\" (feat. Eric Kupper) from ''Realness'' (season 8)\n\n===Original music challenges===\nOccasionally throughout the show, and in every season finale from season 9 onward, the cast will be challenged to write their own original verses to new or existing RuPaul songs.\n* \"CoverGirl\" (feat. [[BeBe Zahara Benet]], [[Nina Flowers]], & Rebecca Glasscock) (Original version from ''Champion'') (Season 1)\n* \"Can I Get an Amen?\" (feat. [[Alaska Thunderfuck|Alaska]], [[Alyssa Edwards]], [[Coco Montrese]], [[Detox Icunt]], [[Ivy Winters]], [[Jade Jolie]], [[Jinkx Monsoon]], & [[Roxxxy Andrews]]) (Original version from ''Born Naked'') (Season 5)\n* \"Oh No She Better Don't\" (feat. [[Adore Delano]], [[BenDeLaCreme]], [[Bianca Del Rio]], [[Courtney Act]], [[Darienne Lake]], [[Joslyn Fox]], [[Laganja Estranja]], [[Milk (drag queen)|Milk]], & [[Trinity K. Bonet]]) (Season 6)\n* \"Get Ready to Clock\" (parody of \"Sissy That Walk\" from ''Born Naked'') (feat. Max, [[Violet Chachki]], & Jaidynn Diore Fierce) (Season 7)\n* \"Tan With You\" (parody of \"Dance With U\" from ''Born Naked'') (feat. Trixie Mattel, [[Miss Fame]], [[Pearl (drag queen)|Pearl]], & Katya) (Season 7)\n* \"I Got Paid\" (parody of \"Let the Music Play\" from ''Born Naked'') (feat. [[Mrs. Kasha Davis]], [[Ginger Minj]], Kennedy Davenport, & Kandy Ho) (Season 7)\n* \"Les Chicken Wings\" (feat. [[Robbie Turner]], [[Kim Chi]], & Naomi Smalls) (Season 8)\n* \"Street Meatz\" (feat. [[Bob the Drag Queen]], [[Thorgy Thor]], & [[Acid Betty]] (Season 8)\n* \"Dragometry\" (feat. [[Derrick Barry]], [[Chi Chi DeVayne]], & Naysha Lopez) (Season 8)\n* \"Category Is\" (feat. [[Peppermint (drag queen)|Peppermint]], [[Sasha Velour]], [[Shea Coulee]], & [[Trinity Taylor]]) (Original version from ''Butch Queen'') (Season 9)\n* \"American\" (feat. [[Aquaria (drag queen)|Aquaria]], [[Asia O'Hara]], [[Eureka O'Hara|Eureka]], & [[Kameron Michaels]]) (Original version from ''American'') (Season 10)\n* \"Queens Everywhere\" (feat. [[A'keria C. Davenport]], [[Brooke Lynn Hytes]], [[Silky Nutmeg Ganache]], [[Vanessa Vanjie Mateo]] & [[Yvie Oddly]]) (Original version from ''Queen of Queens'') (Season 11)\n* \"Read U Wrote U\" (Ellis Miah Remix) (feat. [[Alaska Thunderfuck|Alaska]], Detox Icunt, [[Katya Zamolodchikova|Katya]], & Roxxxy Andrews) (All Stars 2)\n* \"Drag Up Your Life\" (feat. Bebe Zahara Benet, BenDeLaCreme, [[Kennedy Davenport]], [[Shangela Laquifa Wadley|Shangela]], & [[Trixie Mattel]]) (All Stars 3)\n* \"Sitting on a Secret\" (feat. [[Aja (entertainer)|Aja]], [[Chi Chi DeVayne]], Milk, [[Morgan McMichaels]], & [[Thorgy Thor]]) (All Stars 3)\n* \"Kitty Girl\" (feat. BeBe Zahara Benet, Kennedy Davenport, Shangela, & Trixie Mattel) (Original version from ''American'') (All Stars 3)\n* \"Don't Funk It Up\" (feat. [[Gia Gunn]], [[Latrice Royale]], Manila Luzon, Trinity The Tuck & [[Valentina (drag queen)|Valentina]]) (All Stars 4)\n* \"Evrybody Say Love\" (feat. [[Naomi Smalls]], [[Monique Heart]], [[Farrah Moan]], & Mon\u00e9t X Change) (All Stars 4)\n* \"Super Queen\" (feat. Mon\u00e9t X Change, Monique Heart, Naomi Smalls, & Trinity The Tuck) (Original version from ''[[Christmas Party (RuPaul album)|Christmas Party]]'') (All Stars 4)\n* \"Break Up (Bye Bye)\" (Frock Destroyers version feat. [[Baga Chipz]], Blu Hydrangea, & [[Divina de Campo]]; Filth Harmony version feat. [[The Vivienne]], [[Cheryl Hole]], & Crystal) (UK Series 1)\n* \"To the Moon\" (feat. Baga Chipz, Divina De Campo & The Vivienne) (UK Series 1)\n* \"I'm That Bitch\" (feat. [[Brita Filter|Brita]], Crystal Methyd, Gigi Goode, Heidi N Closet, Jackie Cox, Nicky Doll, & Widow Von'Du) (Season 12)\n* \"You Don't Know Me\" (feat. Aiden Zhane, Dahlia Sin, Jaida Essence Hall, Jan, Rock M. Sakura & Sherry Pie) (Season 12)\n\n===Other music challenges===\nIn addition to the original music challenges, sometimes the contestants will be challenged to lip sync or sing live to a new original song. For seasons 7 and 8, the top 3 queens each had songs specifically written for them to lip-sync on the finale. Some of these have been released as singles, and an album was released containing some of songs written by [[Lucian Piane]] entitled ''RuPaul's Drag Race: The Rusical'' on April 22, 2016.\n* \"The Diva Awards\" (Season 2)\n* \"[[Champion (RuPaul album)|Lady Boy]]\" (feat. [[Tyra Sanchez]], [[Raven (drag queen)|Raven]], [[Jujubee (drag queen)|Jujubee]], [[Tatianna]], [[Pandora Boxx]], [[Jessica Wild]], & [[Sahara Davenport]]) (Season 2)\n* \"Superstar\" (feat. [[Sutan Amrull|Raja]], [[Manila Luzon]], [[Alexis Mateo]], [[Yara Sofia]], [[Carmen Carrera]], & [[Shangela Laquifa Wadley|Shangela]]) (Original version from ''Glamazon'') (Season 3)\n* \"Bitch Ball\" (Season 4)\n* \"Sugar Babies\" (Season 5)\n* \"So Much Better Than You\" (feat. Latrice Royale, [[Willam Belli|Willam]], [[Phi Phi O'Hara]], [[Sharon Needles]], [[Chad Michaels]], & [[DiDa Ritz]]) (Season 4)\n* \"Shade: The Rusical\" (feat. Courtney Act, BenDeLaCreme, Adore Delano, Bianca Del Rio, Darienne Lake, Joslyn Fox, Trinity K. Bonet, Laganja Estranja, Milk, Gia Gunn, & April Carri\u00f3n) (Season 6)\n* \"Always Wear a Jewel\" (Season 6)\n* \"Glamazonian Airways\" (Season 7)\n* \"Eggs\" (feat. Ginger Minj & Trixie Mattel) (Season 7)\n* \"Cha Cha Heels\" (feat. Katya & Kennedy Davenport) (Season 7)\n* \"Poo\" (feat. Pearl, Miss Fame, & Violet Chachki) (Season 7)\n* \"Too Many Daddies\" (written for Violet Chachki) (Season 7)\n* \"Pray & Slay\" (written for Ginger Minj (Season 7)\n* \"Sleepwalker\" (written for Pearl (Season 7)\n* \"Rucapella (Bitch Perfect)\" (Season 8)\n* \"[[Jerri Blank]] Tribute\" (Season 8) \n* \"I Don't Like To Show Off\" (written for Bob the Drag Queen) (Season 8)\n* \"Fat, Fem & Asian\" (written for Kim Chi (Season 8)\n* \"Legs\" (written for Naomi Smalls) (Season 8)\n* \"Kardashian: The Musical\" (Season 9)\n* \"PharmaRusical\" (Season 10)\n* \"Madonna: The Unauthorized Rusical\" (feat. Brita, Crystal Methyd, Gigi Goode, Heidi N Closet, Jackie Cox, Jaida Essence Hall, Jan, Sherry Pie, & Widow Von'Du) (Season 12)\n* \"Cher: The Unauthorized Rusical\" (feat. Aquaria, Eureka, Kameron Michaels, [[Miz Cracker]], Mon\u00e9t X Change, & [[The Vixen]]) (Season 10)\n* \"Trump: The Rusical\" (Season 11)\n* \"Glamazon (Savage Sisters)\" (All Stars 1)\n* \"Cover Girl (Fanny Shosha)\" (All Stars 1)\n* \"Jealous of My Boogie (V3)\" (All Stars 1)\n* \"Good vs. Evil\" (All Stars 1)\n* \"Herstory of the World\" (All Stars 2)\n* \"Divas Live\" (All Stars 3)\n* \"Best Judies\" (All Stars 4)\n\n===Runway songs===\nEvery season, a new song is played as the queens present their looks on the main stage runway. When RuPaul walks down the runway, the song played in every season is \"CoverGirl\" from [[Champion (RuPaul album)|Champion]]\n* \"CoverGirl\" (season 1)\n* \"[[Jealous of My Boogie|Jealous of My Boogie\" (Gomi & RasJek Mix)]] from ''Jealous of My Boogie - The RuMixes'' and ''Essential, Vol. 2'' (season 2)\n* \"Champion\" (DJ BunJoe's Olympic Mix) from ''Drag Race'' (season 3)\n* \"Glamazon\" from ''[[Glamazon]]'' (season 4)\n* \"I Bring the Beat\" from ''[[Glamazon]]'' (season 5)\n* \"Sissy That Walk\" from ''[[Born Naked]]'' (seasons 6-7)\n* \"The Realness\" (feat. Eric Kupper) from ''[[Realness]]'' (season 8)\n* \"Forever - Alonsso Franco (Reworked with elements of \u2018Spotlight\u2019 from ''[[American (album)|American]]'' and \u2018Category is...\u2019 from Butch Queen) (season 9)\n* \"Snapshot\" (feat. Mark Macutchi) from ''[[Remember Me: Essential, Vol. 1]]'' (season 10)\n* \"Mighty Love\" (feat. KUMMERSPECK) from ''[[American (album)|American]]'' (season 11)\n* \"Superstar\" (Hollywood Royalty Remix) from ''[[SuperGlam DQ]]'' (season 12)\n* \"Sexy Drag Queen (dootdoot 'doot-swift' Remix)\" from ''[[Essential, Vol. 2]]'' (All Stars 1-3)\n* \"Super Queen (Runway Remix)\" from ''[[Christmas Party (RuPaul album)|Christmas Party]]'' (All Stars 4)\n\n===''The Covergurlz'' & ''Covergurlz 2''===\nRuPaul confirmed via Twitter that an album, in which each contestant from season six covered a song from his catalog, would be released. The album, titled [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 6)#RuPaul Presents: The CoverGurlz|''RuPaul Presents: The CoverGurlz'']], was released on January 28, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/ru...lz/id798824990|title=iTunes - Music - RuPaul Presents the CoverGurlz by RuPaul|work=iTunes}}</ref>\n\nSimilar to season six, each of the seventh season's contestants covered a song that was previously recorded by RuPaul. The album is titled [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 7)#RuPaul Presents: CoverGurlz2|''RuPaul Presents: CoverGurlz2'']] and was released on February 3, 2015. The album also features the single \"New York City Beat\", a song by RuPaul featuring Michelle Visage.<ref name=\"covergurlz itunes\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/rupaul-presents-covergurlz2/id960466886|title=iTunes - Music - RuPaul Presents CoverGurlz2 by RuPaul|work=iTunes}}</ref>\n\n==Related media==\n;''[[RuPaul's Drag U]]'' (2010\u20132012)\n:''RuPaul's Drag U'' is a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] that ran from 2010 to 2012. In each episode, three women are paired with former ''Drag Race'' contestants (\"Drag Professors\"), who give them [[Drag (clothing)|drag]] [[makeover]]s and help them to access their \"inner divas\".<ref name=\"FBDragU\">{{cite web| last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Facebook Rupaul's Drag U | work = | publisher = | date =April 12, 2010 |url=https://www.facebook.com/RuPaulsDragU?v=info | doi = | accessdate =April 12, 2010 }}</ref> Since each episode was taped in Los Angeles over a period of one month, most of the professors were queens living in Southern California.\n;''[[RuPaul's Drag Race All Stars]]'' (2012\u2013)\n:''RuPaul's Drag Race All Stars'' is a spin-off in which past contestants return and compete for a spot in the Drag Race Hall of Fame. The show's format is similar to that of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'', with challenges and a panel of judges. The first season of ''All Stars'' started six months after the conclusion of ''Drag Race'''s [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 4)|fourth season]]. Twelve queens from seasons 1-4 competed over six episodes. The second ''All Stars'' competition aired in 2016, a few months after the [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 8)|season eight]] finale. This season featured ten queens, selected from seasons 2-7, competing in eight episodes, with a special reunion episode. The third ''All Stars'' season was announced in August 2017, and the cast was revealed during a VH1 television special, which aired on October 20, 2017. Ten queens selected from seasons 1-9 competed over the course of eight episodes.\n;''[[The Switch Drag Race]]'' (2015\u2013)\n:''The Switch Drag Race'' is a licensed [[glocalization]] of ''Drag Race'' that premiered in October 2015 on Chilean television channel [[Mega (Chilean television channel)|Mega]]. As in ''Drag Race'', queens compete in \"mini challenges\" and a main challenge, and are evaluated by a panel of judges. Similarly to ''Drag Race'', ''The Switch'' requires contenstants to lip sync, dance, and perform impersonations.\n;''[[Drag Race Thailand]]'' (2018\u2013)\n:In October 2017, it was announced that [[Kantana Group]] had acquired the rights to produce its own version of ''Drag Race''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://instinctmagazine.com/post/thailand-bought-rights-produce-its-own-rupauls-drag-race |title=Thailand Bought The Rights To Produce Its Own RuPaul's Drag Race |date=October 19, 2017}}</ref> Season 1 of ''Drag Race Thailand'' was met with successful ratings on [[Thailand|Thai]] television. It was later announced that the first season will premiere in the [[United States]] in May 2018. The first season also made stirs in the Asian LGBT community, the most prominent of which was a campaign to establish versions of ''Drag Race'' in the [[Philippines]] and [[Taiwan]] as well, two of the most LGBT-accepting nations in all of [[Asia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com//entertainment/spotlight/181956-rupaul-drag-race-rodrigo-duterte-donald-trump|title=Why 'RuPaul's Drag Race' is essential viewing in a post-Duterte/Trump world|first=Chino L.|last=Cruz|website=Rappler|accessdate=6 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=By bluebay700 |url=http://bluebay700.com/2017/06/10/philippines-was-well-represented-at-rupauls-drag-race-season-9-finale/ |title=Philippines Was Well Represented At RuPaul's Drag Race Season 9 Finale |publisher=bluebay700 |date=2017-06-10 |accessdate=2018-09-19}}</ref>\n;''[[Dancing Queen (U.S. TV series)|Dancing Queen]]'' (2018)\n:In April 2013, RuPaul confirmed that he planned to [[Executive producer|executive-produce]] a spin-off of ''Drag Race'' that stars season five and ''All Stars'' season two contestant [[Alyssa Edwards]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Lloyd|first=Sarah Anne|url=http://www.wetpaint.com/network/articles/whoa-rupaul-took-alyssa-edwards-to-the-mtv-movie-awards|title=Whoa Rupaul Took Alyssa Edwards to the MTV Movie Awards|publisher=Wetpaint|accessdate=April 24, 2013}}</ref> Alyssa Edwards has confirmed that the spin-off's title is ''Beyond Belief'' (later retitled as ''Dancing Queen''),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dragofficial.com/1/post/2013/06/update-on-alyssa-edwards-new-spin-off.html|title=Update on Alyssa Edwards' New Spin-Off 'Beyond Belief'|work= Drag Official}}</ref> and that his dance company in [[Mesquite, Texas]] is the setting.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Renzi|first=Dan|url=http://www.queerty.com/no-t-no-shade-alyssa-edwards-takes-her-next-step-20130615/|title=No T No Shade Alyssa Edwards Takes Her Next Step|magazine=Queerty|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref> The series aired on Netflix on October 5, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8471649/drag-race-alyssa-edwards-netflix-docu-series-trailer|title='Drag Race's Alyssa Edwards to Star in Netflix Docu-Series: Watch the Trailer|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/rupauls-drag-race-alyssa-edwards-star-dancing-queen-docuseries-netflix-1202450180/|title='RuPaul's Drag Race' Alum Alyssa Edwards To Star In 'Dancing Queen' Docuseries On Netflix|last=Petski|first=Denise|date=2018-08-22|work=Deadline|access-date=2018-08-25|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/08/22/alyssa-edwards-dancing-queen-trailer-netflix/|title='RuPaul's Drag Race' star Alyssa Edwards battles angry dance moms in 'Dancing Queen' series trailer|work=EW.com|access-date=2018-08-25|language=en}}</ref>\n;''[[RuPaul's Drag Race UK]]'' (2019\u2013)\n:In April 2014, [[chat show]] host and television presenter [[Jonathan Ross]] told the ''[[Daily Star (British newspaper)|Daily Star]]'' that a UK version of the show was being planned, fronted by [[Jodie Harsh]] instead of RuPaul. Ross said, \"I've been working with Jodie on a UK version of RuPaul's Drag Race. Unfortunately, we have had to take a break because of some family issues. But we're hoping to pick it up again in the near future. I am definitely serving 'middle-aged-realness!'\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/showbiz/goss/372632/Jonathan-Ross-starts-hunt-for-Britain-s-next-drag-starstar|title=Jonathan Ross starts hunt for Britain's next drag starstar - Wired - Latest Celebrity Gossip, Controversy & News - Daily Star|work=Dailystar.co.uk}}</ref> RuPaul has since explained, \"I think that because truTV has brought all the seasons of ''Drag Race'' to the UK I think that that might be something that will happen much sooner\u2026. I think that people will fall so in love with the show, I think that the hunger and the thirst for a UK version will probably happen. That's my prediction.\"<ref name=\"movie\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/rupaul-reveals-rupauls-drag-race-6294306|title=RuPaul reveals RuPaul's Drag Race MOVIE in new magazine dedicated to all things drag|author=Carl Greenwood|date=21 August 2015|work=mirror}}</ref> To coincide with TruTV airing new seasons of the show in the UK, RuPaul hosted a competition to find a UK Ambassador for ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' with judges Jonathan Ross and [[Katie Price]] in May 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/rupauls-drag-race-uk-jonathan-5775001|title=RuPaul's Drag Race UK: Jonathan Ross joins search for a drag queen superstar to represent us|author=Carl Greenwood|date=27 May 2015|work=mirror}}</ref> The Vivienne, a drag queen from [[Liverpool]], won the competition and created [[Video blog|vlogs]] to accompany ''Drag Race'' episodes on truTV as well as visiting the set for the eighth season of ''Drag Race'' in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.out.com/popnography/2015/5/29/rupaul-crowns-first-ever-uk-drag-ambassador-vivienne|title=RuPaul Crowns First Ever UK Drag Ambassador: The Vivienne|work=out.com}}</ref> \n:On December 5, 2018, it was announced that the British version of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' will be an eight-part series filmed in London based on local drag queens and is set to air on [[BBC Three (online)|BBC Three]] in 2019. Visage has confirmed via social media that she will appear as a judge.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-46452824|title=RuPaul's Drag Race coming to the UK|date=2018-12-05|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-12-05|language=en-GB}}</ref> RuPaul announced there will be a challenge inspired by [[Meghan Markle]].The first confirmed celebrity judge was [[Game of Thrones]] actor, [[Maisie Williams]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2019/05/20/game-of-thrones-maisie-williams-drag-race-uk/|title=Game of Thrones' Maisie Williams to guest judge RuPaul's Drag Race UK \u00b7 PinkNews|website=www.pinknews.co.uk|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>\n;''[[RuPaul's Secret Celebrity Drag Race (Season 1)|RuPaul's Secret Celebrity Drag Race]]'' (2020)\n:On October 22nd, 2019, RuPaul officially announced that a spin-off of Drag Race was being developed, where Drag Race alumni give Celebrities drag makeovers and compete for the title  America's Next Celebrity Drag Superstar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/10/rupauls-celebrity-drag-race-new-show|title=RuPaul Announces Drag Race Spin-Off Featuring All-Celebrity Competitors|last=Desta|first=Yohana|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n;''[[Drag Race Canada]]'' (2020)\n:On June 27, 2019, [[OutTV]] and [[Bell Media]]'s streaming service [[Crave (streaming service)|Crave]] announced that they had co-commissioned a Canadian version of ''Drag Race''. Rights to the series, as well as the U.S. and British versions, will be shared by OutTV and Crave going forward.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.c21media.net/craves-drag-race-canada-on-starting-line/|title=Crave's Drag Race Canada on starting line|website=C21media|language=en-us|access-date=2019-07-02}}</ref> Additionally, [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 11)|Season 11]] runner-up [[Brooke Lynn Hytes]] has been confirmed as one of the judges, becoming the first queen in the history of the Drag Race franchise to become a permanent judge after having been a contestant.\n;''[[Drag Race Australia]]'' (2020)\n:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2019/08/26/rupauls-drag-race-australia-announced-host/|title=RuPaul's Drag Race Australia has been announced|date=August 26, 2019}}</ref>\n;Brazilian localization\n:In August 2017, a Brazilian version of the show was announced. It was scheduled to air in late 2018, however nothing has been released since the original announcement.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://f5.folha.uol.com.br/colunistas/fernando-oliveira/2017/08/drag-rupaul-vira-ao-pais-para-reality-show.shtml |title=Drag RuPaul vir\u00e1 ao pa\u00eds para reality show |work=[[Folha de S.Paulo]] |date=August 23, 2017}}</ref>\n;Feature film\n:In August 2015, RuPaul revealed that a movie featuring all of the contestants was in the works. \"We've got a director for it, we've got a light script, but it just needs a little more retooling and scheduling.\"<ref name=\"movie\" />\n\n==Home media==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"5\"\n|-\n! Season !! Release date !! Special features !! Discs\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|December 6, 2011<ref name=\"DVDS1\">{{cite web|title=RuPaul's Drag Race: Season 2|publisher =LOGOOnline Shop|url=http://shop.logotv.com/RuPauls-Drag-Race-Season-