taining video clips]]\n", "name_user": "84.0.213.3", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apollo_program"}
{"title_page": "Everyday Life (Coldplay album)", "text_new": "{{Short description|2019 studio album by Coldplay}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Everyday Life\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Coldplay]]\n| cover      = Coldplay - Everyday Life.png\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2019|11|22|df=yes}}\n| recorded   = 2007\u20132009, 2018\u20132019\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n* The Bakery, London\n* The Beehive, London\n* Umbria, Italy\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Alternative rock]]|[[experimental rock]]|[[art rock]]|[[post-britpop]]}}\n| length     = 53:35 (CD and vinyl)<br>52:55 (digital)<br>57:11 (Japanese CD Edition)\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Parlophone]]|[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Rik Simpson]]|Dan Green|Bill Rahko|Angel Lopez|Federico Vindver|[[Max Martin]]}}\n| chronology = [[Coldplay]]\n| prev_title = [[Live in Buenos Aires (Coldplay album)|Live in Buenos Aires]]\n| prev_year  = 2018\n| next_title = Coldplay: Reimagined\n| next_year  = 2020\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Coldplay]] studio album\n | type       = studio\n | prev_title = [[A Head Full of Dreams]]\n | prev_year  = 2015\n | title      = Everyday Life\n | year       = 2019\n}}\n{{Singles\n | name        = Everyday Life\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Orphans (Coldplay song)|Orphans]]\n | single1date = {{Start date|2019|10|24}}\n | single2     = [[Arabesque (Coldplay song)|Arabesque]]\n | single2date = {{Start date|2019|10|24}}\n | single3     = [[Everyday Life (song)|Everyday Life]]\n | single3date = {{Start date|2019|11|3}}\n | single4     = [[Champion of the World (song)|Champion of the World]]\n | single4date = {{Start date|2020|02|24}}\n}}\n}}\n'''''Everyday Life''''' is the eighth And final studio album by British rock band [[Coldplay]]. It was released on 22 November 2019 by [[Parlophone]] in the United Kingdom and [[Atlantic Records]] the United States. It is a [[double album]] (released as a single CD), with the first half titled '''''Sunrise''''' and the other '''''Sunset'''''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.readdork.com/news/coldplay-look-to-be-teasing-a-new-double-album-according-to-a-letter-sent-to-fans|title=Coldplay look to be teasing a new double album, according to a letter sent to fans|website=[[Dork (magazine)|Dork]]|date=21 October 2019|accessdate=22 October 2019}}</ref> The release coincided with 'Coldplay: Everyday Life - Live in Jordan' in which performances of each half of the album were live streamed from [[Amman|Amman, Jordan]] at sunrise and sunset respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.coldplay.com/livestream-concerts-in-jordan-with-youtube-announced/|title=Coldplay - Official Site|date=November 1, 2019|website=Coldplay|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nThe album was recorded from 2018 \u2013 mid 2019 with some songs coming from the ''[[Viva la Vida or Death and All His Friends|Viva la Vida]]'' recording sessions in 2007-2008. Many returning producers and collaborators joined the band's efforts including: \"The Dream Team\" ([[Rik Simpson]], Dan Green, Bill Rahko), [[Davide Rossi]],and [[Emily Lazar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iheart.com/content/2019-11-26-coldplay-celebrates-everyday-life-explains-meaning-behind-double-album/|title=Coldplay Celebrates 'Everyday Life,' Explains Meaning Behind Double Album|last=Fields|first=Taylor|date=November 26, 2019|website=www.iheart.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> Speculation about the album\u2019s existence persisted in the time between its release and the previous record as rumors circulated that the band would discontinue following their release of ''[[A Head Full of Dreams]]'', the subsequent [[A Head Full of Dreams Tour|world tour]], and [[Coldplay: A Head Full of Dreams|documentary]] about their first 20 years as a band. This is the second studio album to not be supported by a major tour after 2014\u2019s ''[[Ghost Stories (Coldplay album)|Ghost Stories]]''. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Savage|first=Mark|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-34743843|title=Coldplay reveal 'final' album|date=2015-11-06|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/will-coldplay-release-a-new-album-in-2019-fans-think-theyve-figured-out-a-release-date-10182221|title=Coldplay Fans Are Convinced That This Is When The Band's New Album Will Drop|website=Bustle|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nThe album received positive reviews from music critics. Most praised its experimental [[Alternative rock|alt rock]] direction and the shift to politically charged lyrics. ''Everyday Life'' was praised for its varied song styles in contrast to their old roots of their previous albums ''[[Parachutes (Coldplay album)|Parachutes]]'' to ''[[Viva la Vida or Death and All His Friends]]''. Some were less enthusiastic about the execution of the experimental style, citing the albums lack of a thematic consistency.<ref name=\"Stereogum\" /><ref name=\"The Guardian\" /> Commercially, ''Everyday Life'' earned the band their eighth number-one album on the [[UK Albums Chart]] and their seventh top 10 US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] album. It was supported by 4 singles, \u201c[[Orphans (song)|Orphans]]\u201d / \u201c[[Arabesque (Coldplay song)|Arabesque]]\u201d in October of 2019, \u201c[[Everyday Life (song)|Everyday Life]]\u201d in November, and \u201c[[Champion of the World (song)|Champion of the World]]\u201d in February of 2020. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/coldplay/chart-history/TLP|title=Coldplay|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/7620/coldplay/|title=Coldplay {{!}} full Official Chart History {{!}} Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion==\nOn 13 October 2019, black-and-white posters featuring the band teasing the album, and the date \"22 November 1919\" appeared in various cities around the world, including [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[Berlin]], [[Hong Kong]] and [[Sydney]].<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/coldplay-tease-new-double-album-mysterious-letter-fans-2559182|title=Coldplay tease new \"double album\" in mysterious letter to fans|website=[[NME]]|last=Reilly|first=Nick|date=21 October 2019|accessdate=22 October 2019}}</ref> On 19 October, a video teaser featuring the same theme was also released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/coldplay-announce-new-album/|title=Coldplay Announce New Album|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last1=Minsker|first1=Evan|last2=Strauss|first2=Matthew|date=21 October 2019|accessdate=22 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O22N1lH5sss|title=November 22, 1919|via=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref> Two days later, several fans began receiving typewritten notes from the band in the mail.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8533641/coldplay-double-album-everyday-life-teaser|title=Coldplay Just Announced a Double Album in the Most Old-Fashioned Way Possible|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Rowley|first=Glenn|date=21 October 2019|accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote| quote = dear friends / my typing isn't very good i'm sorry / I and we hope wherever you are you're ok / for the last 100 years or thereabouts we have been working on a thing called Everyday Life / in the classifieds you might write 'double album for sale, one very careful owner' / one half is called 'sunrise', the other 'sunset' / it comes out 22 november / it is sort of how we feel about things / we send much love to you from hibernation /\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0648 \u062d\u0628 / chris, jonny, guy and Will Champion, esq.| author = Coldplay, in a typewritten note to their fans}}\n\nOn 23 October, the track listing was announced by the band in the advertising sections of several newspapers around the world. This included the ''[[North Wales Daily Post]]'', where guitarist [[Jonny Buckland]] \"once had a holiday job\".<ref name=\"NME Tracklist\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/coldplay-everyday-life-tracklist-announcement-2560362|title=Coldplay announce tracklist for new album 'Everyday Life' in local Welsh newspaper|work=NME|last=Moore|first=Sam|date=23 October 2019|accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref> The 19 November edition of the New Zealand newspaper ''[[Otago Daily Times]]'' featured advertisements containing lyrics to the tracks from the album.<ref name=\"ODT lyrics\">{{cite news |last=Edwards |first=Jono |date=19 November 2019 |title=Coldplay picks ODT for exclusive peek at lyrics |url=https://www.odt.co.nz/news/dunedin/coldplay-picks-odt-exclusive-peek-lyrics |work=[[Otago Daily Times]] |access-date=22 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Surround sound===\nThe album was recorded using [[Dolby Atmos]] technology.\n\n===Live performances===\nDuring an online press conference on 1 November, Coldplay announced they would perform ''Everyday Life'' in two shows in [[Amman|Amman, Jordan]] on 22 November, the release date of the album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8542076/coldplay-everyday-life-livestream-jordan-youtube|title=Coldplay Announce 'Everyday Life' Live Stream in Jordan|website=Billboard|last=Pace|first=Lilly|date=1 November 2019|accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref> The first show showcased the band performing the first half of the album ''Sunrise'' at 4:00 a.m. GMT, and the second show featured the performance of ''Sunset'' at 2:00 p.m. GMT.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2019/11/coldplay-announce-concert-livestream-carrie-brownstein-fred-armisen-amman-jordan-watch/|title=Coldplay Team Up With Carrie Brownstein and Fred Armisen to Announce Concert Livestream|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|last=Arcand|first=Rob|date=2 November 2019|accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref> The shows, which were livestreamed on [[YouTube]], marked the band's first ever performances in the country. Both shows were promoted and advertised as [[YouTube Originals]]. The two shows were performed without an audience, but the following night the band performed their first public show at the Citadel in Jordan's capital city Amman.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/features/stand-love-peace-brotherhood-inside-coldplays-spectacular-sermon-mount-amman-jordan-2571529|title='We stand for love and peace and brotherhood' \u2013 inside Coldplay's spectacular sermon on the mount in Jordan|work=[[NME]]|last=Stubbs|first=Dan|date=25 November 2019|accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> On 18 November, the band announced a one-off show at the [[London Natural History Museum]] on 25 November, with proceeds from the show to be donated to an environmental charity. However, the band announced that they would not play a world tour to promote the album until they had addressed concerns regarding travel and the environmental impact of the shows.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-50490700|title=Coldplay to pause touring until concerts are 'environmentally beneficial'|website=[[BBC News]]|date=21 November 2019|accessdate=21 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Singles==\n\"[[Orphans (Coldplay song)|Orphans]]\" and \"[[Arabesque (Coldplay song)|Arabesque]]\" were released as the album's lead singles on 24 October 2019 on the [[Annie Mac]] show on [[BBC Radio 1]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/coldplay-share-new-songs-orphans-and-arabesque-listen/|title=Coldplay Share New Songs \"Orphans\" and \"Arabesque\": Listen|last=Strauss|first=Matthew|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=24 October 2019|accessdate=24 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/coldplay-orphans-arabesque-903248/|title=Coldplay Release 'Orphans,' 'Arabesque' From Double LP 'Everyday Life'|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|last=Shaffer|first=Claire|date=24 October 2019|accessdate=24 October 2019}}</ref> The next day, the music video for Orphans came out.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PXKYA-zmzTY|title=Coldplay - Orphans (Official Video)|website=YouTube|date=25 October 2019|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> Arabesque does not have one. \"[[Everyday Life (Coldplay song)|Everyday Life]]\" was released as the third single on 3 November 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/coldplay-drops-song-everyday-life-054629418.html|title=Coldplay drops new song 'Everyday Life' after playing Saturday Night Live|last=Bucksbaum|first=Sydney|website=[[Yahoo! Entertainment]]|date=3 November 2019|accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref> The music video was released on December 9, 2019. On 20 November 2019 a music video for \"[[Daddy (Coldplay song)|Daddy]]\" and a lyric video for \"[[Champion of the World (song)|Champion of the World]]\" were released;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/watch-a-snippet-of-aardman-animations-amazing-animated-coldplay-video-for-new-single-daddy-2567719|title=Here's Coldplay's dreamy new Aardman Animations video for 'Daddy', and new song 'Champion Of The World'|last=Jones|first=Damian|date=November 20, 2019|website=[[NME]]}}</ref> the latter was also released as a single on 25 February 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allaccess.com/triple-a/future-releases|title=Future Releases (Triple A)|work=[[All Access]]|accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allaccess.com/alternative/future-releases|title=Future Releases (Alternative Radio)|work=[[All Access]]|accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kayI9QB1-IA|title=Coldplay - Champion Of The World (Official Video)|website=YouTube|date=25 February 2020|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> The \"Cry Cry Cry\" music video, which was co-directed by Chris' girlfriend [[Dakota Johnson]], was released on 14 February 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lA9-TQE3lTM|title=Coldplay - Cry Cry Cry (Official Video)|website=YouTube|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> \"Trouble in Town\" music video was released on 12 March 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwe.youtube.com/watch?v=aKlwJROuo-Q|title=Coldplay - Trouble In Town (Official Video)|website=YouTube|date=12 March 2020|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album reviews\n| ADM = 6.8/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://anydecentmusic.com/review/10173/Coldplay-Everyday-Life.aspx|title=Everyday Life by Coldplay reviews|publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|accessdate=2 December 2019}}</ref>\n| MC = 73/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/everyday-life/coldplay|title=Everyday Life by Coldplay Reviews and Tracks|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=28 November 2019}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite news|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/everyday-life-mw0003329823|title=Everyday Life \u2013 Coldplay|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|last=Yeung|first=Neil Z.|accessdate=21 November 2019}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev2score = B\u2212<ref name=\"The A.V. Club\">{{cite web|url=https://music.avclub.com/coldplay-runs-away-from-coldplay-on-the-wildly-uneven-e-1839946885|title=Coldplay runs away from Coldplay on the wildly uneven Everyday Life|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|last=Modell|first=Josh|date=22 November 2019|accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''\n| rev3score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"mcmormick\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/what-to-listen-to/coldplay-everyday-life-review-16-heart-on-sleeve-songs-one-greatest/|title=Coldplay, Everyday Life, review: '16 heart-on-sleeve songs from one of the greatest British bands of the century'|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|last=McCormick|first=Neil|authorlink=Neil McCormick|date=19 November 2019|accessdate=19 November 2019|url-access=subscription|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev4score = B+<ref name=\"Entertainment Weekly\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/music-reviews/2019/11/22/coldplay-everyday-life-review/|title=Coldplay navigates existential dread on the catchy, curveball-filled Everyday Life|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Johnston|first=Maura|authorlink=Maura Johnston|date=22 November 2019|accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev5score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/nov/21/coldplay-everyday-life-review-parlophone-chris-martin|title=Coldplay: Everyday Life review \u2013 surefire hits and dodgy experiments|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|authorlink=Alexis Petridis|date=21 November 2019|accessdate=21 November 2019}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev6score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"The Independent\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/coldplay-everyday-life-review-album-gun-control-syria-chris-martin-a9211046.html|title=Coldplay review, Everyday Life: A fascinating, occasionally brilliant curio|work=[[The Independent]]|last=White|first=Adam|date=22 November 2019|accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev7score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"NME review\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/album/coldplay-everyday-life-review-2577508|title=Coldplay \u2013 'Everyday Life' review: a confounding experiment from a deceptively forward-thinking band|work=[[NME]]|last=Krol|first=Charlotte|date=21 November 2019|accessdate=28 November 2019}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev8score = 6.8/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/coldplay-everyday-life/|title=Coldplay: Everyday Life|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Sodomsky|first=Sam|date=25 November 2019|accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev9score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/coldplay-everyday-life-918255/|title=Coldplay Get Admirably Real on the Organically Expansive \u2018Everyday Life\u2019|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|last=Hermes|first=Will|authorlink=Will Hermes|date=26 November 2019|accessdate=27 November 2019}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Times]]''\n| rev10score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"The Times\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/coldplay-everyday-life-review-back-to-the-goodish-old-days-5rh9r7x22|title=Coldplay: Everyday Life review \u2014 back to the goodish old days|work=[[The Times]]|last=Hodgkinson|first=Will|authorlink=Will Hodgkinson|date=22 November 2019|accessdate=26 November 2019|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Everyday Life'' received generally positive reviews from critics. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalised rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album has an average score of 73 out of 100 based on 26 reviews, which indicates \"generally favorable reviews\", becoming the band's second highest-scored album on the website, behind ''[[A Rush of Blood to the Head]]''.<ref name=\"MC\" /> Writing for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', [[Neil McCormick]] acclaimed the experimentation of the album, stating that ''Everyday Life'' \"feels organic, analogue and playful as Coldplay dip into different musical genres,\" and further highlighted Martin's \"golden gift for melody, almost simplistically direct lyrics and emotive crooning.\"<ref name=\"mcmormick\" /> Chris DeVille of ''[[Stereogum]]'' considered that the album's experimentation and use of multiple genres worked \"more often than not,\" and commended the band's \"more nuanced\" exploration of social issues, concluding that it was a \"truly great album.\"<ref name=\"Stereogum\">{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2064318/coldplay-everyday-life-review/franchises/premature-evaluation/|title=Premature Evaluation: Coldplay ''Everyday Life''|work=[[Stereogum]]|last=DeVille|first=Chris|date=21 November 2019|accessdate=21 November 2019}}</ref> In her review for ''[[NME]]'', Charlotte Krol claimed that the record \"is proof that Coldplay are more adventurous than they're often given credit for,\" despite some of its songs being \"sometimes more exciting in theory than in practice.\"<ref name=\"NME review\" />\n\nOther reviewers were less enthusiastic about the album's experimentation. Although ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s [[Alexis Petridis]] considered it a \"laudable intention,\" he found the album \"wildly uneven\" and was critical of the \"lyrical vagueness\" of various songs dealing with \"sociopolitical matters,\" but complimented \"a couple of acoustic tracks with genuine emotional heft.\"<ref name=\"The Guardian\" /> In the same vein, Adam White of ''[[The Independent]]'' described the album as a \"valiant, if flawed, attempt to break from tradition\" and a \"fascinating, occasionally brilliant curio,\" but considered that the band were \"still very much figuring out how to respond to a world that has become meaner, dirtier and crueller,\" nevertheless considering the effort admirable.<ref name=\"The Independent\" /> Ludovic Hunter-Tilney of the ''[[Financial Times]]'' found the album \"platitudinising,\" but considered Martin's songwriting \"more focused than usual;\" he additionally noted the album's \"quirky production\" and balancing of \"contradictory urges to play it safe and take a risk.\"<ref name=\"ft\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/c7050f1a-0af0-11ea-bb52-34c8d9dc6d84|title=Coldplay shake things up with psych rock, Afrobeat and gospel karaoke on new album Everyday Life|work=[[Financial Times]]|last=Hunter-Tilney|first=Ludovic|date=22 November 2019|accessdate=22 November 2019|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n''Everyday Life'' debuted at number one on the [[UK Albums Chart]], becoming Coldplay's eighth UK number-one album. The album was the third-fastest selling album of 2019 in the UK, behind ''[[No.6 Collaborations Project]]'' and ''[[Divinely Uninspired to a Hellish Extent]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/coldplays-everyday-life-beats-robbie-williamss-christmas-album-to-number-1-on-the-official-albums-chart__27838/|title=Coldplay's Everyday Life beats Robbie Williams's Christmas album to Number 1 on the Official Albums Chart|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|last=Copsey|first=Rob|date=29 November 2019|accessdate=2 December 2019}}</ref> It also debuted at number seven on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] with 48,000 [[album-equivalent unit]]s, including 36,000 pure album sales.<ref name=\"BB200\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8545115/trippie-redd-no-1-album-billboard-200-chart|title=Trippie Redd Rules With First No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart|work=Billboard|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=1 December 2019|accessdate=2 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = 27:59\n| headline = ''Sunrise''\n| title1 = Sunrise\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Guy Berryman]]|[[Jonny Buckland]]|[[Will Champion]]|[[Chris Martin]]|[[Davide Rossi]]}}\n| extra1 = Rossi\n| length1 = 2:31\n| title2 = Church\n| writer2 = {{hlist|Berryman|Buckland|Champion|Martin|[[Amjad Sabri]]|Rossi|[[Stargate (production team)|Mikkel Eriksen]]|[[Stargate (production team)|Tor Hermansen]]|[[Jacob Collier]]|Norah Shaqur}}\n| extra2 = {{hlist|[[ Rik Simpson]]|Dan Green|Bill Rahko|Angel Lopez{{ref|b|[b]}}|Federico Vindver{{ref|b|[b]}}}}\n| length2 = 3:50\n| title3 = Trouble in Town\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Berryman|Buckland|Champion|Martin}}\n| extra3 = {{hlist|Simpson|Green|Rahko}}\n| length3 = 4:38\n| title4 = Broken<!-- Stylisation is noted below the track list -->\n| writer4 = {{hlist|Berryman|Buckland|Champion|Martin}}\n| extra4 = {{hlist|Simpson|Green|Rahko}}\n| length4 = 2:30\n| title5 = [[Daddy (Coldplay song)|Daddy]]\n| writer5 = {{hlist|Berryman|Buckland|Champion|Martin}}\n| extra5 = {{hlist|Simpson|Green|Rahko}}\n| length5 = 4:58\n| title6 = WOTW / POTP<!-- The liner notes spelling out the song title is noted below the track list -->\n| writer6 = {{hlist|Berryman|Buckland|Champion|Martin}}\n| extra6 = {{hlist|Simpson|Green|Rahko}}\n| length6 = 1:16\n| title7 = [[Arabesque (Coldplay song)|Arabesque]]  \n| writer7 = {{hlist|Berryman|Buckland|Champion|Martin|Drew Goddard|[[Femi Kuti]]|[[Stromae|Paul Van Haver]]}}\n| extra7 = {{hlist|Simpson|Green|Rahko}}\n| length7 = 5:40\n| title8 = When I Need a Friend\n| writer8 = {{hlist|Berryman|Buckland|Champion|Martin}}\n| extra8 = {{hlist|Simpson|Green|Rahko|[[John Metcalfe (composer)|John Metcalfe]]}}\n| length8 = 2:35\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = 24:52\n| headline = ''Sunset''\n| title1 = Guns\n| writer1 = {{hlist|Berryman|Buckland|Champion|Martin}}\n| extra1 = {{hlist|Simpson|Green|Rahko}}\n| length1 = 1:55\n| title2 = [[Orphans (Coldplay song)|Orphans]]\n| writer2 = {{hlist|Berryman|Buckland|Champion|Martin|Moses Martin}}\n| extra2 = {{hlist|Simpson|Green|Rahko|[[Max Martin]]{{ref|a|[a]}}|Lopez{{ref|b|[b]}}|Vindver{{ref|b|[b]}}}}\n| length2 = 3:17\n| title3 = \u00c8k\u00f3\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Berryman|Buckland|Champion|Martin}}\n| extra3 = {{hlist|Simpson|Green|Rahko}}\n| length3 = 2:37\n| title4 = Cry Cry Cry\n| writer4 = {{hlist|Berryman|Buckland|Champion|Martin|[[Jacob Collier]]|[[Bert Berns|Bertrand Berns]]|[[Jerry Ragovoy]]}}\n| extra4 = {{hlist|Simpson|Green|Rahko}}\n| length4 = 2:47\n| title5 = Old Friends\n| writer5 = {{hlist|Berryman|Buckland|Champion|Martin}}\n| extra5 = {{hlist|Simpson|Green|Rahko}}\n| length5 = 2:26\n| title6 = {{lang|fa|\u0628\u0646\u06cc \u0622\u062f\u0645}}\n| writer6 = {{hlist|Berryman|Buckland|Champion|Martin|[[Alice Coltrane]]|Harcourt Whyte|[[Saadi Shirazi]]}}\n| extra6 = {{hlist|Simpson|Green|Rahko}}\n| length6 = 3:14\n| title7 = [[Champion of the World (song)|Champion of the World]]\n| writer7 = {{hlist|Berryman|Buckland|Champion|Martin|Andy Monaghan|[[Scott Hutchison]]|Simon Liddell}}\n| extra7 = {{hlist|Simpson|Green|Rahko|Martin{{ref|a|[a]}}|Lopez{{ref|b|[b]}}|Vindver{{ref|b|[b]}}}}\n| length7 = 4:17\n| title8 = [[Everyday Life (song)|Everyday Life]]\n| writer8 = {{hlist|Berryman|Buckland|Champion|Martin|[[John Metcalfe (composer)|John Metcalfe]]}}\n| extra8 = {{hlist|Simpson|Green|Rahko|Lopez{{ref|b|[b]}}|Vindver{{ref|b|[b]}}}}\n| length8 = 4:18\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| headline = ''Everyday Life''{{nobold|&nbsp;\u2014 Japanese edition (bonus track)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.jp/\u3010Amazon-co-jp\u9650\u5b9a\u3011\u30a8\u30f4\u30ea\u30c7\u30a4\u30fb\u30e9\u30a4\u30d5-\u30c7\u30ab\u30b8\u30e3\u30b1\u4ed8-\u30b3\u30fc\u30eb\u30c9\u30d7\u30ec\u30a4/dp/B07ZK8R8L6|title=Everyday Life [Japan Bonus Track] COLDPLAY CD Album|website=[[Amazon.co.jp]]|accessdate=21 November 2019}}</ref>}}\n| title9 = Flags\n| note9 = bonus track\n| length9 = 3:36\n| extra9 = \n}}\n\n'''Notes'''\n* {{sup|{{ref|a|[a]}}}} indicates a co-producer\n* {{sup|{{ref|b|[b]}}}} indicates an additional producer\n* Producers Rik Simpson, Dan Green and Bill Rahko are credited collectively as \"The Dream Team\".\n* \"Broken\" is stylised as \"BROK\u0428N\" on physical copies, while on digital media is stylised as \"BrokEn\".\n* \"WOTW / POTP\" stands for and is rendered in the physical edition liner notes as \"Wonder of the World / Power of the People\".\n* \"Church\" features female vocals by Norah Shaqur.\n* \"Broken\" features a choir consisting of Mabvuto Carpenter, Denise Green, Stevie Mackey, Neka Hamilton, Surrenity XYZ, LaMarcus Eldrigde and Dorian Holley.\n* \"Arabesque\" features vocals by [[Stromae]].\n* \"When I Need a Friend\" features the [http://www.london-voices.com London Voices] choir conducted by [[Ben Parry (musician)|Ben Parry]].\n* \"God = Love\" is only available on the physical CD edition of the album. It consists of a 30 second field recording of clock tower bells spread across 8 tracks. The track titles of this section are revealed when the CD is loaded into a computer.\n* \"Orphans\" features a choir consisting of Marwa Kreitem, Nadeen Fanous, Garine Antreassian, Bashar Murad, Norah Shaqur, Apple Martin, Moses Martin, Ben Oerlemans, Bill Rahko, Aluna and Jocelyn 'Jozzy' Donald.\n* \"\u00c8k\u00f3\" features backing vocals by [[Tiwa Savage]].<ref>{{cite web |author1=Debola Abimbolu |title=Tiwa Savage Joins Coldplay on \"\u00c8k\u00f3\"|url=https://thenativemag.com/music/tiwa-savage-joins-coldplay-african-influenced-everyday-life-album/ |website=Native |date=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* \"{{lang|fa|\u0628\u0646\u06cc \u0622\u062f\u0645}}\" (\"''Bani Adam''\") features the voice of Dr. Shahrzad (Sherry) Sami reciting Persian poet [[Saadi Shirazi|Saadi's]] [[Bani Adam|poem]] in Persian. The expression translates literally to \"Children of Adam\", or \"Human Beings\" within the context of the poem.\n* \"Everyday Life\" features backing vocals by Marianna Champion.\n* \"Church\", \"Cry Cry Cry\" and \"Everyday Life\" feature backing vocals by [[Jacob Collier]].\n\n'''Sample credits'''\n* \"Church\" beat inspiration by [[Stargate (music producers)|Mikkel Eriksen]] and [[Stargate (music producers)|Tor Erik Hermansen]]. Contains a sample from \"Jaga Ji Laganay\", as performed and written by Amjad Sabri.\n* \"Trouble in Town\" contains a rendition of \"Jikelele\", sung by the children of the African Children's Feeding Scheme (ACFS), Soweto, Johannesburg. It also contains a recording of an incident involving racial profiling of pedestrians by a Philadelphia police officer in 2013.<ref>{{Citation|title=Police unlawful harassment and racial profiling 9/27/13 Philly,Pa|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G4exZ-jXgWE|language=en|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref> \n* \"Arabesque\" includes an excerpt from the film ''Music Is the Weapon''.\n* \"When I Need a Friend\" includes a sample from the film ''Everything Is Incredible''.\n* \"Cry Cry Cry\" contains elements from \"[[Cry Baby (Garnet Mimms song)|Cry, Baby]]\", written by [[Bert Berns]] and [[Jerry Ragovoy]].\n* \"{{lang|fa|\u0628\u0646\u06cc \u0622\u062f\u0645}}\" contains a sample from \"The Sun\", written by [[Alice Coltrane]].\n* \"{{lang|fa|\u0628\u0646\u06cc \u0622\u062f\u0645}}\" and \"Champion of the World\" contain a sample from \"Otuto Nke Chukwu\", as performed by Harcourt Whyte.\n* \"Champion of the World\" contains an interpolation of \"Los Angeles, Be Kind\", written by [[Scott Hutchison]], Simon Lidell and Andy Monaghan.\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from the \"Orphans / Arabesque\" liner notes.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite AV media|people=[[Coldplay]]|date=24 October 2019|title=Orphans / Arabesque|url=https://www.qobuz.com/gb-en/album/orphans-arabesque-coldplay/pdw3skm2cep8a|access-date=26 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026005528/https://www.qobuz.com/gb-en/album/orphans-arabesque-coldplay/pdw3skm2cep8a|archive-date=26 October 2019|url-status=live|format=[[Music download|digital download]]|publisher=[[Parlophone]]}}</ref>\n{{Col-start}}\n{{Col-break}}\n{{Unbulleted list|'''Recording'''|{{Small|'''Coldplay'''}}}}\n* [[Guy Berryman]] \u2013 bass guitar, percussion\n* [[Will Champion]] \u2013 drums and percussion, keyboards,backing vocals\n* [[Jonny Buckland]] \u2013 guitars\n* [[Chris Martin]] \u2013 lead vocals, guitars, keyboards, piano\n{{Small|'''Additional vocalists'''}}\n* Aluna \u2013 choir vocal \n* Garine Antreassian \u2013 choir vocal \n* Jocelyn 'Jozzy' Donald \u2013 choir vocal\n* Nadeen Fanous \u2013 choir vocal \n* Marwa Kreitem \u2013 choir vocal\n* Apple Martin \u2013 choir vocal\n* Moses Martin \u2013 choir vocal\n* [[Bashar Murad]] \u2013 choir vocal \n* Ben Oerlemans \u2013 choir vocal\n* Bill Rahko \u2013 choir vocal \n* Norah Shaqur \u2013 choir vocal \n* [[Stromae]] \u2013 vocals \n{{Small|'''Additional musicians'''}}\n* [[Ransome-Kuti family|Omorinmade Anikulapo-Kuti]] \u2013 [[alto saxophone]] {{Small|(track 7)}}\n* Babatunde Ankra \u2013 [[trombone]] {{Small|(track 7)}}\n* Drew Goddard \u2013 guitar \n* Daniel Green \u2013 keyboards \n* [[Le Trio Joubran|Samir Joubran]] \u2013 guitar\n* [[Wissam Joubran]] \u2013 guitar \n* [[Le Trio Joubran|Adnan Joubran]] \u2013 guitar\n* [[Femi Kuti]] \u2013 horn \n* Made Kuti \u2013 orchestrionics \n* Ayoola Magbagbeola \u2013 [[tenor saxophone]] \n* [[Max Martin]] \u2013 keyboards \n* Gbenga Ogundeji \u2013 trumpet \n* Bill Rahko \u2013 keyboards\n* [[Davide Rossi]] \u2013 [[String instrument|strings]] \n* [[Rik Simpson]] \u2013 keyboards\n{{Col-break}}\n{{Unbulleted list|'''Production'''|{{Small|'''Main'''}}}}\n* Daniel Green \u2013 [[Record producer|producer]] {{Small|(track 7, 10)}}, [[Programming (music)|programming]] \n* [[Emily Lazar]] \u2013 [[Mastering (audio)|mastering]]\n* Max Martin \u2013 producer and programming \n* Bill Rahko \u2013 producer {{Small|(tracks 7, 10)}}, programming \n* Rik Simpson \u2013 producer {{Small|(tracks 7, 10)}}, programming \n* [[Spike Stent|Mark \"Spike\" Stent]] \u2013 [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]]\n{{Small|'''Assistant'''}}\n* Erwan Abbas \u2013 assistant engineering \n* Chris Allgood \u2013 assistant mastering\n* Lionel Capouillez \u2013 additional engineering \n* Michael Freeman \u2013 assistant mixing \n* Matt Glasbey \u2013 assistant engineering\n* Pierre Houle \u2013 additional engineering \n* Adnan Joubran \u2013 additional engineering\n* Matt Latham \u2013 assistant engineering \n* Baptiste Leroy \u2013 assistant engineering\n* Bastien Lozier \u2013 additional engineering \n* Issam Murad \u2013 assistant engineering\n* Lance Robinson \u2013 additional engineering\n* Davide Rossi \u2013 additional engineering \n* Anthony De Souza \u2013 assistant engineering \n* Federico Vindver \u2013 additional engineering\n* Matt Wolach \u2013 assistant mixing \n{{Col-end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2019)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{album chart|Australia|1|artist=Coldplay|album=Everyday Life|rowheader=true|accessdate=30 November 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Austria|5|artist=Coldplay|album=Everyday Life|rowheader=true|accessdate=5 December 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Flanders|1|artist=Coldplay|album=Everyday Life|rowheader=true|accessdate=30 November 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Wallonia|1|artist=Coldplay|album=Everyday Life|rowheader=true|accessdate=30 November 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardCanada|3|artist=Coldplay|rowheader=true|accessdate=3 December 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Czech|4|date=201948|rowheader=true|accessdate=3 December 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Denmark|6|artist=Coldplay|album=Everyday Life|rowheader=true|accessdate=4 December 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Netherlands|1|artist=Coldplay|album=Everyday Life|rowheader=true|accessdate=30 November 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Finland|8|artist=Coldplay|album=Everyday Life|rowheader=true|accessdate=1 December 2019}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| French Albums ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://snepmusique.com/les-tops/le-top-de-la-semaine/top-albums/?semaine=48?&annee=2019&categorie=Top%20Albums|title=Top Albums (Week 48, 2019)|publisher=Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|language=French|accessdate=3 December 2019}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n{{album chart|Germany4|4|id=394656|artist=Coldplay|album=Everyday Life|rowheader=true|accessdate=29 November 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Hungary|3|year=2019|week=48|rowheader=true|accessdate=6 December 201